This pattern of promising poor quality or under-developed project ideas in election campaigns is troubling because politicians find it very hard to back down from promises, even when it becomes apparent that the original assumptions about the project were not well founded (see \Vref{box:hunter} on the Hunter Expressway).

\begin{bigbox*}{Case study -- Hunter Expressway -- more than 350 per cent over budget}{box:hunter}

\subsubsection*{Government reluctance to change course when facts change}

A plan to build a Maitland bypass as part of the New England Highway in northern New South Wales was floated as early as 1983.\footcite{Bill2009NationBuildingProgramAmendment} The preferred route for what eventually became the Hunter Expressway was decided in 2001 and expected to cost ``more than \$335 million'' in 2002.\footcite{DIRD2002FedGovkeepsNSWMoving}

In 2007 the funding commitment was increased to \$887 million by the Federal coalition Government as an election pledge.\footcite{Bill2009NationBuildingProgramAmendment} After winning the 2007 election, the new Labor Government cooled on the idea. In 2008, Joel Fitzgibbon, the then Labor Member for Hunter, observed that: ``First, the F3 link was conceived in the mid 1980s and there have been big changes in traffic movements and residential and commercial settlement patterns since then. Second, the cost of the project is now \$1,700 million (\$1.7 billion) and it has a very low benefit to cost ratio (meaning it provides tax-payers with a low-value solution).''\footcite{Bill2009NationBuildingProgramAmendment}

The government commissioned a review in 2008,\footcite{DIRD2008LowerHunterTransportNeedsStudy} following which funding of \$1.7 billion was committed in 2009.\footcite{RMS2010Hunter} Federal Liberal Member for nearby Paterson, Bob Baldwin criticised the government's prevarication ``because we (the coalition) had committed to it as a 
government''.\footcite{Bill2009NationBuildingProgramAmendment} Mr Baldwin emphasised the persistence of Support the Link, a local lobby group that pushed hard for the road.\footcite{Bill2009NationBuildingProgramAmendment}
The project was completed in 2014.\footcite{RMS2016Hunter}

While the final benefit cost ratio has not been published, these comments from politicians reveal the difficulty governments experience in reneging on commitments made very early in a project’s life, even after the facts of the project change significantly.

