\section{Risk measurement}\label{risk-measurement}

Australia's guidance on risk minimisation is generally of a high standard. However, this guidance is not sufficient, as it is inevitable that some cost risks will be impossible, or prohibitively expensive, to eliminate. These remaining risks need to be accurately measured, so that they can be factored into investment decisions and efficiently managed throughout a project's life.

As discussed in section \ref{risk-assessment-should-be-comprehensive}, the critical shortcoming of risk management on Australia's transport infrastructure projects is that the guidance regarding how to measure unavoidable project risks is poor. This is because the guidance on how to quantify project risks is:

\begin{itemize}{}
\item
  inconsistent within and across jurisdictions,
\item
  incomplete, as most guidance does not provide advice on how to assess unknown risks or extreme and unlikely events, and
\item
  often contains insufficient information for the recommended risk measurement methodologies to be properly implemented.
\end{itemize}

This section reviews each of these shortcomings in detail and provides state-specific examples of opportunities for improvement.

\subsection{Guidance is inconsistent}\label{guidance-is-inconsistent}

Guidelines which apply to the same jurisdiction often recommend different approaches to risk measurement. For instance, Probability pricing is required for federal funding, yet only half the risk measurement guidance provided at the federal level discusses probability pricing.

The \emph{National Partnerships Agreement on Land Transport Infrastructure Projects} \footcite{COAG2014NationalPartnershipAgreementInfrastructure}, the Australian Transport Council’s \emph{National Guidelines for Transport System Management in Australia} \footcite{ATC2006NGTSM3}, Infrastructure Australia’s \emph{Business Case Template} \footcite{Australia2016InfrastructureAustraliaAssessmentc}, the \emph{Best Practice Cost Estimation Standard for Publicly Funded Road and Rail Construction} \footcite{DIRD2008BPCEPFRRC} and BITRE's \emph{Overview of Project Appraisal for Land Transport} \footcite{BITRE2014Overviewofprojectappraisalforlandtransport} require or discuss probability pricing. However, Infrastructure Australia's \emph{Assessment Framework} \footcite{Australia2016InfrastructureAustraliaAssessmentb}, the \emph{HB 158:2010 Handbook on delivering assurance based on ISO 31000:2009} \footcite{StandardsAustralia2010DeliveringassurancebasedonISO31000} and BITRE's \emph{Risk in Benefit Cost Analysis} \footcite{BITRE2005RiskinCostBenefitAnalysis} do not.

In Victoria, three key guidelines on risk measurement each recommend only part of the toolkit, and a different part in each case:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  the Department of Treasury and Finance's \emph{Technical Guidelines on Economic Evaluation of Business Cases}\footcite{VicDTF2013EconomicEvaluationforBusinessCasesTechnicalguidelines} requires only sensitivity analysis,
\item
  the Victorian Insurance Management Authority's \emph{Practice Guide}\footcite{VMIA2016PracticeGuide} requires only the calculation of the expected value of project risks, and
\item
  the Department of Treasury and Finance's \emph{Business Case Template}\footcite{VicDTF2016Fullbusinesscasetemplate} and \emph{Gateway Review Process}\footcite{VicDTF2016GatewayReviewProcess} only requires reference class forecasting.
\end{itemize}

Such inconsistencies within jurisdictions obfuscate proper process and make the conceptual dependencies between tools unclear.

Risk measurement guidance should also be consistent across jurisdictions. This is because each state must comply with both its own guidelines and the Commonwealth's whenever it seeks project funding from the Commonwealth to supplement its own funding of a project. Where state and commonwealth guidance differ, multiple versions of the same analysis are required.

For example, Victoria's business case on the Western Distributor has two sets of benefit cost ratios in order to conform to different guidance of the two levels of government.\footnote{"Western distributor ref"} Neither of these benefit cost ratios appears more correct than the other. Rather, they are two imperfect estimates of the same concept. As both estimates would have come at a significant financial cost, Australia's project appraisal processes could be made more cost efficient by aligning the analysis required across each jurisdiction.

As it stands, risk measurement guidance is very inconsistent between each state and the Commonwealth. \Vref{consistency-table} shows that the expected value approach to estimating risks' costs is the only approach that is recommended consistently across all jurisdictions.

